 {"id":"frankenjax-od34","title":"Make batched fixture timeouts return without joining timed-out workers","description":"Review finding [HIGH]. Commit 0985d27 changed run_transform_fixture_bundle_batched in crates/fj-conformance/src/lib.rs to record timed-out worker handles, but the function then joins all timed_out_handles before returning (current lines around 1145-1186). That means case_timeout does not bound wall-clock runtime: a timed-out case with a long or hung worker still blocks the whole batched run at the final join.

Reproduction to add: construct a TransformFixtureBundle with one case having simulated_delay_ms = 5000 and BatchRunnerConfig { case_timeout: Duration::from_millis(1) }. Measure elapsed time for run_transform_fixture_bundle_batched. Expected behavior for a timeout runner is to return a Timeout report promptly after roughly the configured timeout; current behavior waits for the delayed worker during the final join and returns only after the worker finishes. A genuinely hung worker would hang the harness indefinitely despite emitting a timeout report.

Suggested fix: preserve bounded fan-out without joining timed-out workers on the critical return path. Options include a scoped worker pool with cooperative cancellation, a persistent bounded runner, or clearly documenting and renaming the timeout as classification-only. Add an elapsed-time regression test so future code cannot reintroduce timeout-as-blocking-join semantics. Validate with rch cargo test -p fj-conformance test_batch_runner.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-29T00:48:42.510310052Z","created_by":"cod_2_reviewer","updated_at":"2026-04-29T01:47:57.221289946Z","closed_at":"2026-04-29T01:47:57.219499755Z","close_reason":"Detached timed-out batch workers from the return path and added elapsed-time regression coverage","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
